text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!Giving an exam in Indian English%0a%0a:Author: Mihir_D%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIndian English has several instances of verbs being used as they are in native languages like Hindi. %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aStandard American and British English have conventions for using particular verbs in particular contexts. Due to direct translations from native languages such as Hindi, alternative verbs are common in Indian English.%0a%0aSome examples:%0a%0aStandard English: "take/write/sit for" a test%0aIndian English (IndE) also has: "give" a test%0aIn Hindi, this phrase could translate to "परीक्षा दो", where "दो" means "give".%0a%0aStandard English: "turn off" a light%0aIndE also has: "close" a light ("off" a light is used as well)%0aIn Hindi, this phrase could translate to "लाइट बंद करें", where "बंद" means "close".%0a%0aStandard English: I "live" here%0aIndE also has: I "stay" here%0aIn Marathi, this phrase would translate to "मी इथे राहातो", where "राहातो" usually means "I stay"%0a%0aSimilar literal translations exist for "keep" (IndE) to mean "put" and "cut" (IndE) to mean "hang up (a call)". Idioms are also translated leading to "eating my brains/head" (मेरा दिमाग खा रहा है) being used when someone is bugging you.%0a%0aAn example of a non-verb being literally translated is "good name", meaning "शुभ नाम" which is how people politely ask for full names as opposed to a nickname.%0a%0aThese variations are commonly used and accepted, as English is often a second language for many Indians, so many try to translate directly from their native languages. These variations still make sense even for a non IndE speaker, so there is not much of a barrier to understanding. Many IndE speakers (like my parents) use some of these constructions without even realizing it. %0a%0aOn the other hand, there are also American English constructions that are particularly confusing for IndE speakers, such as "the alarm went off" to mean the alarm turned on.%0a%0aSource: https://www.ling.upenn.edu/~jason2/papers/ienglish.htm%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210417-140555-154790#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Hong Kong English / Chinglish exhibits a similar pattern in the way verbs are used in Indian English %0a-> - Mingkang_L%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe way verbs are used in Hong Kong English / English spoken in other parts of China is quite similar to the case of Indian English.  It also exhibits direct, literal translation from Chinese to English.%0a%0aWhile in standard English, people say "turn on / off" a light. Hong Kong English / Chinglish also has “open / close” a light. This translate to the phrase 开(open)/关 (close) 灯 (light) in Simplified Chinese, or  開(open) /關(close) 燈 (light) in Traditional Chinese, which is very similar to the case in Hindi.%0a%0aWhile in standard English we say “read a book”, “watch a movie,” and “look at that bird,” the word “look” can replace the verb of all three expressions in Chinglish. This is also likely a result of direct, literal translation from Chinese to English, as in “看(look) 电影(film)” “看(look)书(book)” “看(look)那(that)只(counter, referring to a small, animate object) 鸟(bird)”%0a%0aAn example of a non-verb being literally translated in Chinese is “add oil”, which is an expression used as an encouragement and support to a person, literally 加(add) 油(oil). This expression has been been recognized by more and more people by speakers of standard English. A more well-known example is “long time no see,” which corresponds to the Chinese expression “好久(long time) 不(no) 见(look/see) “ in Mandarin or “好耐(long time) 冇 (no)見 (see)” in Cantonese. The expression “lose face” is directly transliterated from 丢(lose/throw away) 脸(face) to mean suffering a loss of respect. Despite these differences, English spoken in Hong Kong is highly intelligible to listeners from elsewhere, so there’s not much of a barrier to understanding, just like the case of Indian English.%0a%0aSource:Pang, T. (2003). Hong Kong English: A stillborn variety? English Today, 19(2), 12-18. doi:10.1017/S0266078403002037%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210417-140555-154790#%0a#foxbegin 210422-033036-440010#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ESL Classes  %0a-> - sgangu%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI definitely think that Indian English formed because of translating our first language directly into the closest words in English. There is no way for non-Native English speakers to know that the alarm going "off" means that it is actually ringing. Since English was not my first language, I was placed in English as a second language (ESL) classes in elementary school primarily for speaking Indian english. I remember once I had spent enough time in school, my English become like that of a native speaker and I no longer used literal translations from Telugu. It was at this point that I was taken out of ESL classes, but I sort of didn't really understand the need for them in the first place. Most non standard American English is pretty understandable and ESL classes should not be for those who simply just speak English in a different way. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210422-033036-440010#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
