iterally translated is "good name", meaning "शुभ नाम" which is how people politely ask for full names as opposed to a nickname.%0a%3c %0a%3c These variations are commonly used and accepted, as English is often a second language for many Indians, so many try to translate directly from their native languages. These variations still make sense even for a non IndE speaker, so there is not much of a barrier to understanding. Many IndE speakers (like my parents) use some of these constructions without even realizing it. %0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, there are also American English constructions that are particularly confusing for IndE speakers, such as "the alarm went off" to mean the alarm turned on.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.ling.upenn.edu/~jason2/papers/ienglish.htm%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: A:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
